AB  - Integrating the social rejection and brand dilution literatures, this study investigates consumer responses to luxury brand rejection. Across four studies, the findings elaborate that a threat to the luxury brand elicits negative affective responses among consumers with high self-brand connection, while consumers with low self-brand connection are not affected. The findings explain how consumer affective responses mediate behavioral responses to luxury brand rejection causing brand dilution and further elaborate the moderating role of self-construal and the rejection source (in-group vs. out-group) respectively. Specifically, luxury brand rejection by an in-group significantly causes brand dilution than rejection by an out-group for consumers with an interdependent self-construal, while consumers with an independent self-construal only decrease their behavioral intentions when rejection is initiated by an out-group. The findings offer substantive contributions to the social rejection, brand dilution, luxury branding and self-construal theory and provide important managerial insights.
